               Since in the greyscale images only have 1 colour channel opposed to the

               The tensor was then reshaped according to this input shape (which is 32*32*1= 1024).
               The model is a little bit better because it now basically avoids complexities due
               to color, as color is not an important factor in classifying the numbers.

               I started with 5 layers with increasingly more filters, to compensate for the decreasing resolution.
               Zero-padding was used so the model could be deeper. Exploration with a batch size of 96,
               resulted in 3 "blocks" of convolutional layers working well. MaxPooling was then tested and
               implemented after each block to decrease the overfitting. To further prevent overfitting, dropout
               was tested with different rates. In the end, a low dropout rate worked the best. Batch normalization
               further decreased the overfitting. Finally, the number of epochs was adjusted. The final accuracy is
               95% so the model performs very well.

Answer 3.1 (2p)¶

               The most misclassifications seem to involve low numbers (1-4), however
               there are also more lower numbers in the database so they also have 
               the most correct classifications. The most common misclassification is between
               the numbers 2 and 4. After those, misclassifications between the numbers
               6 and 0 are the most common.
